<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <!--
        Sandbox is INTENTIONALLY off for the moment.

        Background: 1.4.10 turned on com.apple.security.app-sandbox
        with a full set of standard sandbox entitlements (network,
        files, calendars, contacts, apple-events). The build runs
        and most features work, BUT Sparkle's Installer XPC
        service can't gain the system authorization it needs to
        replace the bundle from inside the sandbox — installer
        launch fails with -60005 ("Authorization service failed"
        / "Failed copying system domain rights"). OTA updates
        therefore hang at the "launching the installer" step,
        leaving the user stuck on whichever version installed
        sandbox first. Confirmed in Console logs.

        Sparkle's own sandboxing guide
        (https://sparkle-project.org/documentation/sandboxing/)
        documents the workaround: pin the Installer / Downloader
        XPC services into an Application Group keyed by
        `<TEAMID>.<bundle-id>`. That requires a Developer ID
        Team ID — adhoc-signed binaries have no Team ID, so the
        workaround can't be applied to this build.

        Plan: re-enable sandbox immediately after notarization
        with Developer ID is in place. The full entitlements
        block below stays as a comment so it's a one-line flip
        when the cert arrives.

        <key>com.apple.security.app-sandbox</key>
        <true/>
        <key>com.apple.security.network.client</key>
        <true/>
        <key>com.apple.security.network.server</key>
        <true/>
        <key>com.apple.security.files.user-selected.read-write</key>
        <true/>
        <key>com.apple.security.personal-information.calendars</key>
        <true/>
        <key>com.apple.security.personal-information.addressbook</key>
        <true/>
        <key>com.apple.security.automation.apple-events</key>
        <true/>

        Only `time-sensitive` notifications remain declared here
        — same as the pre-1.4.10 state. Note that AMFI still
        silently downgrades this to `.active` on adhoc-signed
        binaries, but declaring it keeps the codebase ready for
        the eventual Developer-ID flip.
    -->

    <key>com.apple.developer.usernotifications.time-sensitive</key>
    <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
